[Student "S"]
{Partner's 2\H is a transfer, so you bid 2\S. Partner now bids 2NT.  

Partner's 2\H is a transfer, so you bid 2\S. Partner now bids 2NT. 

Partner is only inviting, so he must have either 9 or 10 points. And since he chose 2NT as the invitation he must have only 5 \Ss. You will accept the invitation since you have a maximum 1NT opener, and you choose 3NT since you know there is no 8-card \S fit.

South plays 3NT. When West leads the \H5 you have an immediate decision to make.

Winner List: \S = 0 : \H = 1 : \D = 3 : \C = 1 :: Total = 5

It is pretty clear that the 4 additional winners you need will be \Ss. The danger is that when you force out the \SA the defenders might be able to cash 4 \Hs right away. So the immediate decision is whether you take the \HA on the first trick or wait until the second. 

If West has only 4 \Hs it will make no difference what you do because they will only win 3 \H tricks and you will make your contract. So assume that West has a 5-card suit, which means that East has 2 \Hs. West's suit is definitely <b>NOT</b> \H K Q J 5 2; he would have started with the \HK, not the \H5. So you can be sure that East holds either \H K x, \H Q x or \H J x. So what? 

So you should play the \HA immediately. If East puts on his small \H then his lone honor will block the suit the next time it is played. But if he unblocks the honor under dummy's \HA then your \H 10 9 7 will be promoted into a second stopper.

If you play low on the first trick East will win the \HQ and return the \H6 to dummy's \HA. When West gains the lead with his \SA he will cash 3 more \H tricks. Down 1.

Play the \HA on the first trick and East is hog-tied. If he plays low the suit blocks, if he sacrifices his \HQ then your \H 10 9 7 prevents West from running the suit. }
[Play "W"]H5

